In article <9303252315.AA11745@pizzabox.demon.co.uk>,
    gtoal@gtoal.com (Graham Toal) writes:
>	There is a way to foil debuggers, by clearing the single step 
>	interrupt, on which a debugger depends, every few instructions in 
>	the sensitive areas of the code.
>
>*All* of these schemes can be foiled by running under a complete software
>emulation (say of a 386 being emulated on an Alpha, for instance)

Or if you can't afford one of those, just rent or lease an ICE (In Circuit
Emulator) for the processor in question.  These can be had for a few hundred
dollars per week.
